4.1 Initializing from a template
================================

To create a new configuration from scratch, you can use a template.
First, create an empty directory.  Then, run the following command in
the directory:

     nix flake init -t github:emacs-twist/twist.nix

   The template creates the following files:

   • ‘flake.nix’ — the Nix flake with all inputs (nixpkgs, twist, MELPA,
     GNU ELPA, NonGNU ELPA, Emacsmirror) and the call to
     ‘twist.lib.makeEnv’.
   • ‘init.el’ — a starter init file using ‘use-package’.  Add
     ‘use-package’ blocks with ‘:ensure t’ here.
   • ‘early-init.el’ — sets ‘package-enable-at-startup’ to ‘nil’ so that
     ‘package.el’ does not run at startup.
   • ‘lock/’ — an empty lock directory (contains ‘.gitkeep’) where Twist
     will write ‘flake.nix’, ‘flake.lock’, and ‘archive.lock’.
   • ‘README.md’ — quick-start instructions.

   Now you can work on your configuration by adding ‘use-package’ blocks
to ‘init.el’.

   Twist also provides some extra flexibility on configuration:

   • Manage your configuration in an Org file
   • Use an alternative utility other than ‘use-package’, like
     ‘setup.el’

   Otherwise, you can skip the following subsections to start developing
your configuration.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Manual creation of a project boilerplate,  Next: makeEnv options,  Prev: Initializing from a template,  Up: Initial configuration of a project

4.2 Manual creation of a project boilerplate
============================================

Alternatively, if you already have an Emacs configuration built with
Nix, you can migrate your configuration to Twist by tweaking your
configuration.

   This subsection assumes you have a flake for your Emacs
configuration.

* Menu:

* Create flake.nix: Create flakenix.
* Add flake inputs::
* Create a lock directory::
* Define flake outputs::


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Create flakenix,  Next: Add flake inputs,  Up: Manual creation of a project boilerplate

4.2.1 Create flake.nix
----------------------

You must track your configuration in a Git repository, and the root
directory of the repository must contain ‘flake.nix’.  It must follow
the format of Nix flakes (https://nixos.wiki/wiki/Flakes) as recognized
by Nix.  You can run the following command to create a ‘flake.nix’:

     nix flake init


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Add flake inputs,  Next: Create a lock directory,  Prev: Create flakenix,  Up: Manual creation of a project boilerplate

4.2.2 Add flake inputs
----------------------

To use Twist, you have to add ‘github:emacs-twist/twist.nix’ to the
inputs:

     inputs.twist.url = "github:emacs-twist/twist.nix";

   You will also need to add flake inputs for the registries you use.
See *note Registry Configuration:: for details.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Create a lock directory,  Next: Define flake outputs,  Prev: Add flake inputs,  Up: Manual creation of a project boilerplate

4.2.3 Create a lock directory
-----------------------------

You have to create a directory for lock files.  The directory can be
anywhere inside the repository, but not the root directory of the
repository.

   For example, if the directory is named ‘lock’, you can use the
following commands:

     mkdir -p lock
     touch lock/.gitkeep
     git add lock/.gitkeep

   Note that the directory must not be empty.  It must be considered
non-empty by Nix, so you have to create an empty file (e.g.  ‘.gitkeep’)
in the directory and add it to the Git index.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Define flake outputs,  Prev: Create a lock directory,  Up: Manual creation of a project boilerplate

4.2.4 Define flake outputs
--------------------------

A typical ‘flake.nix’ looks like the following.  It uses
‘nixpkgs.lib.genAttrs’ together with the ‘nix-systems/default’ helper to
support multiple systems:

     {
       inputs = {
         nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
         systems.url = "github:nix-systems/default";
         twist.url = "github:emacs-twist/twist.nix";
         # ... registry inputs (melpa, gnu-elpa, etc.) ...
       };

       outputs = { nixpkgs, systems, twist, ... } @ inputs:
         let
           eachSystem = f:
             nixpkgs.lib.genAttrs (import systems)
               (system: f (import nixpkgs { inherit system; }));

           inherit (twist.lib) makeEnv;

           emacsConfig = pkgs: makeEnv {
             inherit pkgs;
             # ... configuration options ...
           };
         in {
           packages = eachSystem (pkgs: rec {
             emacs = emacsConfig pkgs;
             default = emacs;
           });

           apps = eachSystem (pkgs:
             (emacsConfig pkgs).makeApps { lockDirName = "lock"; }
           );
         };
     }

   It is also possible to use other libraries such as flake-utils
(https://github.com/numtide/flake-utils) for the boilerplate.  If you
want to track the Emacs configuration in the same repository as a
NixOS/home-manager configuration, flake-utils-plus
(https://github.com/gytis-ivaskevicius/flake-utils-plus) is recommended,
but it is not described in this manual.

  1. Define a package

     The configuration is built using ‘twist.lib.makeEnv’:

          inherit (twist.lib) makeEnv;

          emacsConfig = pkgs: makeEnv {
            inherit pkgs;
            emacsPackage = pkgs.emacs;

            # The path to the lock directory
            lockDir = ./lock;

            # Your Emacs initialization file(s)
            initFiles = [ ./init.el ];

            # Registries (package-source metadata)
            registries = [ ... ];
          };

     The result is a scope (an attribute set that is also a derivation),
     so you can add it to the flake outputs:

          packages = eachSystem (pkgs: rec {
            emacs = emacsConfig pkgs;
            default = emacs;
          });

  2. Derive apps for administration

     You will also need apps to lock and update packages.  You can add
     these outputs as follows:

          apps = eachSystem (pkgs:
            (emacsConfig pkgs).makeApps { lockDirName = "lock"; }
          );

     You have to set ‘lockDirName’ to the path to the lock directory as
     a string.  ‘makeApps’ exposes two apps:

        • ‘nix run .#lock’ — regenerates ‘lock/flake.nix’ and
          ‘lock/archive.lock’, then runs ‘nix flake lock’ to update
          ‘lock/flake.lock’.
        • ‘nix run .#update’ — refreshes the archive lock
          (‘lock/archive.lock’) with latest packages from ELPA package
          archives.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: makeEnv options,  Next: Registry Configuration,  Prev: Manual creation of a project boilerplate,  Up: Initial configuration of a project

4.3 makeEnv options
===================

The ‘twist.lib.makeEnv’ function accepts the following arguments:

Argument                           Type       Default                            Description
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘pkgs’                             attrset    (required)                         Nixpkgs instance
‘emacsPackage’                     package    ‘pkgs.emacs’                       The Emacs derivation to wrap
‘lockDir’                          path       (required)                         Path to the lock directory (must be a Git-tracked directory)
‘initFiles’                        list       (required)                         List of paths to init files parsed to discover packages
‘registries’                       list       (required)                         List of registry entries; see *note Registry Configuration::
‘initParser’                       function   ‘twist.lib.parseUsePackages {}’    Parser factory; set to ‘twist.lib.parseSetup {}’ for ‘setup.el’ configs
‘initReader’                       function   reads file then runs initParser    Override to customise how init files are read
‘extraPackages’                    list       ‘["use-package"]’ on Emacs <29     Additional package names to install unconditionally
‘localPackages’                    list       ‘[]’                               Package names co-located in this repo; excluded from the generated flake
‘persistMetadata’                  bool       ‘false’                            Persist package metadata JSON in the lock dir (avoids IFD)
‘defaultMainIsAscii’               bool       ‘false’                            Assume all package main files are ASCII (required for some IFD avoidance)
‘exportManifest’                   bool       ‘false’                            Export a manifest file from the wrapper (needed for twist.el hot-reload)
‘nativeCompileAheadDefault’        bool       ‘true’                             Ahead-of-time native compilation for all packages
‘wantExtraOutputs’                 bool       ‘true’                             Build extra outputs of packages, e.g.  Info manuals
‘extraOutputsToInstall’            list       ‘["info"]’ if ‘wantExtraOutputs’   Extra derivation outputs installed into the environment
‘postCommandOnGeneratingLockDir’   string     ‘null’                             Command run at the repository root after ‘generateLockDir’
‘addSystemPackages’                bool       ‘true’                             Feed ‘:system-packages’ declarations from init files into ‘exec-path’
‘inputOverrides’                   attrset    ‘{}’                               Per-package source overrides
‘configurationRevision’            string     ‘null’                             Revision string embedded in the wrapper
‘extraSiteStartElisp’              string     ‘""’                               Extra Emacs Lisp inserted into the site-start file
‘initialLibraries’                 list       ‘null’                             User-supplied list of Emacs built-in library names (overrides auto-detect)


