4.5.1 Org-babel configuration
-----------------------------

The org-babel (https://github.com/emacs-twist/org-babel) library for Nix
allows you to define Twist configurations (and sub-profiles) from a
single Org file using Babel source blocks.  Refer to that library's
documentation for details.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Using a non-stable version of GNU Emacs,  Next: Using a configuration syntax other than use-package,  Prev: Org-babel configuration,  Up: Customization

4.5.2 Using a non-stable version of GNU Emacs
---------------------------------------------

You can pass any Emacs derivation as ‘emacsPackage’.  For example, to
use the latest unstable Emacs from emacs-overlay
(https://github.com/nix-community/emacs-overlay):

     inputs.emacs-overlay.url = "github:nix-community/emacs-overlay";

     # In makeEnv:
     emacsPackage = inputs.emacs-overlay.packages.${system}.emacs-unstable;


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Using a configuration syntax other than use-package,  Prev: Using a non-stable version of GNU Emacs,  Up: Customization

4.5.3 Using a configuration syntax other than use-package
---------------------------------------------------------

By default Twist parses ‘use-package’ declarations to discover which
packages to install.  To use setup.el
(https://github.com/jwiegley/setup.el) instead, pass
‘twist.lib.parseSetup {}’ as ‘initParser’:

     makeEnv {
       # ...
       initParser = twist.lib.parseSetup {};
     }

   Both ‘lib.parseUsePackages’ and ‘lib.parseSetup’ are exported from
‘twist.lib’.


