6.1 Basic workflow
==================

The basic development loop is:

  1. Add or modify ‘use-package’ (or ‘setup.el’) forms in your
     ‘init.el’.
  2. Run ‘nix run .#lock’ to regenerate the lock files for any new
     packages.
  3. Run ‘nix build .#emacs’ (or ‘nix build .#default’) to build the
     configuration.
  4. Run ‘nix run .#update’ periodically to pull in new versions from
     ELPA archives.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Working around sources,  Next: Custom build processes,  Prev: Basic workflow,  Up: Developing the configuration

6.2 Working around sources
==========================

If a package's upstream source is temporarily unavailable or you need to
override it, use ‘inputOverrides’.  For example, to use a GitHub mirror
of a package whose canonical host is unreliable:

     inputOverrides = {
       tramp = _: _: {
         origin = {
           type = "github";
           owner = "emacs-straight";
           repo = "tramp";
           ref = "master";
         };
       };
     };

   To remove build-time files that would otherwise cause build failures:

     inputOverrides = {
       bbdb = _: super: {
         files = builtins.removeAttrs super.files [
           "bbdb-notmuch.el"
           "bbdb-vm.el"
           "bbdb-vm-aux.el"
         ];
       };
     };


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Custom build processes,  Next: Checking the versions of packages,  Prev: Working around sources,  Up: Developing the configuration

6.3 Custom build processes
==========================

Individual package builds can be customised through ‘inputOverrides’ by
overriding attributes in the package's attribute set.  Refer to the
package build derivation in ‘pkgs/emacs/build/’ for available
attributes.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Checking the versions of packages,  Prev: Custom build processes,  Up: Developing the configuration

6.4 Checking the versions of packages
=====================================

‘depsCheck’ attribute is a derivation that checks version boundaries
between Emacs Lisp packages.  If any of the dependencies are lower than
the versions specified in the ‘Package-Requires’ header of their
dependants, it will exit with non-zero:

     nix build .#emacs.depsCheck --print-build-logs

   You can add it to the ‘checks’ output of your flake:

     {
       outputs = inputs:
         let
           emacs = twist.lib.makeEnv { ... };
         in {
           checks.x86_64-linux.elisp-versions = emacs.depsCheck;
         };
     }


