8.1 -dry-run is your friend
===========================

To quickly examine sanity of your configuration, a recommended way is to
build the configuration with ‘--dry-run’ flag:

     nix build .#emacs --dry-run

   If the command fails with non-zero exit code, it is likely that there
is something wrong with your configuration, not an individual Emacs Lisp
package.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Prefer building from sources,  Next: Inspecting the package set,  Prev: --dry-run is your friend,  Up: Tips

8.2 Prefer building from sources
================================

It is recommended to build a package from an upstream whenever possible.

   This is because an archive tarball can be deleted from its server
when the package creates a new release:

     error: unable to download 'https://elpa.gnu.org/packages/vertico-0.18.tar': HTTP error 404 ('Not Found')

            response body:

            <!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
            <html><head>
            <title>404 Not Found</title>
            </head><body>
            <h1>Not Found</h1>
            <p>The requested URL was not found on this server.</p>
            <hr>
            <address>Apache/2.4.51 (Debian) Server at elpa.gnu.org Port 443</address>
            </body></html>

   Use an ‘elpa’ registry entry with ‘auto-sync-only = true’ and fall
back to an ‘archive-contents’ mirror for packages that cannot be built
from source.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Inspecting the package set,  Prev: Prefer building from sources,  Up: Tips

8.3 Inspecting the package set
==============================

You can explore the full package metadata without building:

     nix eval .#emacs.packageInputs --json | jq .


