File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: use-package-always-ensure option,  Next: Emacs Lisp packages that cannot be built with Twist,  Up: Limitations

9.1 use-package-always-ensure option
====================================

use-package (https://github.com/jwiegley/use-package) provides
‘use-package-always-ensure’ option, which makes ‘package.el’ install
packages that have no ‘:ensure’ option set:

     (require 'use-package-ensure)
     (setq use-package-always-ensure t)

   Unfortunately, Twist cannot handle this option well at the time of
writing.

   A better way is to *not* use ‘use-package-always-ensure’ option.  Add
‘:ensure t’ option explicitly to each declaration of a package you want
to install.  This way, you can simply pass the init file to Twist and
also have a choice of explicitly installing some GNU ELPA Core libraries
from the upstream.


File: emacs-twist.info,  Node: Emacs Lisp packages that cannot be built with Twist,  Prev: use-package-always-ensure option,  Up: Limitations

9.2 Emacs Lisp packages that cannot be built with Twist
=======================================================

It is known that Twist cannot build the following packages:

   • ‘pdf-tools’

   Twist simply cannot build these packages for some technical reasons.
It would be better for Twist to support all packages on GNU/NonGNU ELPA
and MELPA, but it is not the case.

   For the latest information, see Issues
(https://github.com/emacs-twist/twist.nix/issues) of Twist.  If you have
found any other packages that cannot be built using Twist, please file
an issue.


